data.en: Euborellia annulipes (or earwigs) have long mandibles/mouthparts and well-developed compound eyes. The antennae are long, filiform and with many segments. They are important natural enemies for FAW as their body structure can enable them to penetrate the hiding places of FAW such as the whorl or the ears. They are usually found in many numbers on a plant as they exhibit maternal care in the protection of hatched eggs and nymphs.

data.en: Coleoptera Coccinellidae (or ladybird beetles) feed on eggs and young larvae of FAW. The size and color of adults can vary among species. data.en: Podisus (or predatory stink bugs) nymphs feed on FAW. They have a high search efficiency, ability to increase population and aggregate quickly when there is abundant prey. Sugar solutions may attract predatory bugs.

data.en: FAW larvae can be affected and killed by a wide range of pathogens. Fungi (such as Beauveria, Metarhizium) infect FAW larvae through the body, and diseased larvae stop feeding, change colour (white, cream, green, reddish or brown) and eventually die as a hard cadaver. Bacteria (Bt) can infect and kill FAW. Viruses (SfGV, SfMNPV) cause the larvae to move to higher parts of the plant where it yellows with blemishes, stops feeding and dies while hanging its head down. The dead larvae are soft and dark in colour. Smashing them will cause further spread of the virus. Always look out for dead or infected larvae in the fields.

data.en: Cotesia marginiventris - the adults of this small wasp deposit multiple eggs in the body of FAW larvae. After about three days when the parasitoid larva emerges, it feeds inside the body tissue of FAW. Soon after after leaving the host, the parasitoid larvae will weave a cocoon on the leaf and turn into a pupa, which hatches within a week.

data.en: There are several different species of stem borers in Africa and Asia (Busseola fusca, Chilo partellus, Eldana saccharina, Sesamia inferens). The creamy white eggs are generally laid in a row under the leaf near the stem, and become dark after a few days. Caterpillars are black when they first hatch but then become light or dark violet, creamy or pinkish white, or yellowish brown. They have no hair and look shiny and smooth. Older caterpillars tunnel into the stem where they pupate.
